                                "start": 0,
                                "stop": 8.421,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Justice Alito has our opinion this morning in case 13-352 B\u0026B Hardware v. Hargis Industries."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 8.421,
                        "stop": 166.243,
                        "byte_start": 0,
                        "byte_stop": 0,
                        "speaker": {
                            "ID": 15068,
                            "name": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.",
                            "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/people\/samuel_alito_jr",
                            "last_name": "Alito",
                            "roles": [
                                {
                                    "id": 2712,
                                    "type": "scotus_justice",
                                    "date_start": 1138687200,
                                    "date_end": 0,
                                    "appointing_president": "George W. Bush",
                                    "role_title": "Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "institution_name": "Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/preson_role\/scotus_justice\/2712"
                                }
                            ],
                            "thumbnail": {
                                "id": 32684,
                                "mime": "image\/png",
                                "size": 44799,
                                "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/sites\/default\/files\/samuel_a_alito_jr_1.png"
                            },
                            "length_of_service": 3531,
                            "identifier": "samuel_alito_jr"
                        },
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 8.421,
                                "stop": 16.306,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "This case concerns the doctrine of issue preclusion which applies when two tribunals are asked to decide the same issue."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 16.306,
                                "stop": 21.372,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The decision of the first tribunal usually must be followed by the second."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 21.372,
                                "stop": 27.859,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "This prevents the same issue from being litigated more than once, saving everyone time and expense."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 27.859,
                                "stop": 32.801,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "This case concerns how issue preclusion applies to Trademark Law."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 32.801,
                                "stop": 52.825,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "In particular, the question is whether a registration decision by the Patent and Trademark Offices, Trademark Trial and Appeal Board can have issue preclusive effect in later trademark infringement litigation in Federal Court and if not whether deference to the board\u0027s decision is warranted."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 52.825,
                                "stop": 69.705,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The petitioner in this case owns the mark SEALTIGHT, spelled S-E-A-L-T-I-G-H-T, while respondent owns the mark SEALTITE, spelled S-E-A-L-T-I-T-E."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 69.705,
                                "stop": 79.261,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The board concluded that respondent\u0027s mark could not be registered because it was so similar to petitioners\u0027 that it was likely to cause confusion."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 79.261,
                                "stop": 84.331,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Petitioner sued respondent for trademark infringement in Federal Court."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 84.331,
                                "stop": 99.202,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "After the board\u0027s registration decision, petitioner argued that the District Court should give issue preclusive effect to the board\u0027s determination meaning that the parties would not re-litigate the issue of likelihood of confusion."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 99.202,
                                "stop": 110.796,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The District Court refused to apply issue preclusion and United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit agreed, holding that issue preclusion was not appropriate for numerous reasons."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 110.796,
                                "stop": 114.483,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "It also declined to defer to the board\u0027s decision."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 114.483,
                                "stop": 118.849,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "We reverse the judgment of the Eighth Circuit and remand for further proceedings."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 118.849,
                                "stop": 127.166,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "We hold that a court should give preclusive effect to board decisions if the ordinary elements of issue preclusion are met."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 127.166,
                                "stop": 149.287,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Because the board applies the same likelihood of confusion standard as Federal Courts, in some cases issue preclusion will be warranted namely where the usages of the mark adjudicated by the board are materially the same as those before the court, but where the board considers different usages neither issue preclusion or deference is warranted."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 149.287,
                                "stop": 153.948,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "This is the same rule of issue preclusion that applies in countless other contexts."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 153.948,
                                "stop": 156.923,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "We do not treat Trademark Law differently."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 156.923,
                                "stop": 166.243,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Justice Ginsburg has filed a concurring opinion; Justice Thomas has filed a dissenting opinion joined by Justice Scalia."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
